<section xml:id="sec_capacitors-in-circuits" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
	<title>Capacitors in Circuits</title>

	<p>We learned about capacitors in Section <xref ref="sec_capacitors"/>. Capacitors can also be elements within a ciruit!</p>
			
	<video youtube="qMJK_sjdUCw"><description>DESCRIPTION</description></video>
			
	<p>Adding capacitors in series and in parallel is opposite to how we add resistors.</p>
	
	<definition>
		<title>Adding Capacitors in Series</title>
		<statement>
			<p>If <m>N</m> capacitors are in series, the total capacitance is: <me>\frac{1}{C_{\mathrm{total}}} = \sum_{i = 1}^{N} \frac{1}{C_i}</me></p>
		</statement>
	</definition>

	<definition>
		<title>Adding Capacitors in Parallel</title>
		<statement>
			<p>If <m>N</m> capacitors are in parallel, the total capacitance is: <me>C_{\mathrm{total}} = \sum_{i = 1}^{N} C_i</me></p>
		</statement>
	</definition>

	<exercises>
		<title>Activities</title>
		<exercise>
			<p>Which of the following statements about capacitors do you think is true? (You may select more than one answer)</p>
			<ol type="a">
				<li><p>Capacitors in series have the same voltage</p></li>
				<li><p>Capacitors in series have the same charge</p></li>
				<li><p>Capacitors in parallel have the same voltage</p></li>
				<li><p>Capacitors in parallel have the same charge</p></li>
			</ol>
			<p>Explain your reasoning.</p>
		</exercise>
	</exercises>
	
</section>

